Southern forces in Yemen have stepped up  protection of oil installations in their stronghold of Aden, correspondents  said Monday.
The south has deployed surface-to-air missiles around Aden refinery, which  has been pumping 140,000 barrels a day despite the war with the north which  erupted on May 5.
Missiles have also been installed around the power station.
Warplanes took off as usual on Monday from Aden airport, despite northern  air and missile attacks which have targeted the facility, correspondents said.  It remained closed however to civilian traffic.
There was a day-time lull in the fighting around the Aden region, apart  from Zinjibar to the east, where northern forces in control of the town came  under fire from southern artillery and warships.
